title: "Extended Example"

<div id="extended-example-and-using-ggplot2" class="section level1">
<h1>Extended Example and Using <code>ggplot2</code></h1>
<p>We will use an example created by the <a href="http://www.iq.harvard.edu/">Institute for Quantitative Social Science</a> at Harvard University. The goal will be to create a copy of a very nice graph from the <a href="http://www.economist.com/node/21541178">economist</a>:</p>
<div class="figure">
<img src="data:image/gif;base64," alt="image" />
<p class="caption">image</p>
</div>
<hr />
<div id="make-sure-you-can-run-this-code" class="section level2">
<h2>Make sure you can Run this Code</h2>
<pre class="r"><code>require(ggplot2)
require(ggrepel)
dat &lt;- read.csv(&quot;https://drive.google.com/uc?export=download&amp;id=0B8CsRLdwqzbzUDJLa1owSVduLTA&quot;)</code></pre>
<hr />
<ul>
<li>We will begin by using the <code>ggplot2</code> package to create this graph.</li>
<li>We will start with a basic plot of <code>CPI</code> (Corruption Index) vs <code>HDI</code> (Human Development Index):</li>
</ul>
<pre class="r"><code># Calls data then the asthetics are x,y and how coloring works
pc1 &lt;- ggplot(dat, aes(x=CPI, y=HDI, color=Region))
#geom_point() is how we choose points to be plotted
pc1 + geom_point()</code></pre>
<hr />
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<hr />
<ul>
<li>This is a long way off from our desired graph. We still need:
<ul>
<li>add a trend line</li>
<li>change the point shape to open circle</li>
<li>label select points</li>
<li>change the order and labels of Region</li>
<li>title, label axes, remove legend title</li>
<li>fix up the tick marks and labels</li>
<li>move color legend to the top</li>
<li>theme the graph with no vertical guides</li>
<li>add model R2 (hard)</li>
<li>add sources note (hard)</li>
<li>final touches to make it perfect (use image editor for this)</li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<hr />
</div>
<div id="trend-lines" class="section level2">
<h2>Trend Lines</h2>
<ul>
<li>This is easy to do if you know the trend line in which you wish to fit.</li>
<li>This time we go with a function <span class="math inline">\(HDI = log(CDI)\)</span>.</li>
</ul>
<pre class="r"><code>(pc2 &lt;- pc1 +
   geom_smooth(aes(group = 1),
               method = &quot;lm&quot;,
               formula = y ~ log(x),
               se = FALSE,
               color = &quot;red&quot;)) +
   geom_point()</code></pre>
<ul>
<li>In this the <code>geom_smooth</code> adds the line to the graph, then on top of that <code>geom_point()</code> adds the points.</li>
</ul>
<hr />
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<hr />
</div>
<div id="change-point-shape" class="section level2">
<h2>Change Point Shape</h2>
<ul>
<li>We begin this by exploring the point options in R, <code>?shape</code>.</li>
<li>The following is an example that the <code>shape</code> page gives us:</li>
</ul>
<pre class="r"><code>## A look at all 25 symbols
df2 &lt;- data.frame(x = 1:5 , y = 1:25, z = 1:25)
s &lt;- ggplot(df2, aes(x = x, y = y)) + 
  geom_point(aes(shape = z), size = 4) + scale_shape_identity() +
  geom_point(aes(shape = z), size = 4, colour = &quot;Red&quot;) +
  scale_shape_identity() + 
  geom_point(aes(shape = z), size = 4, colour = &quot;Red&quot;, fill = &quot;Black&quot;) +
  scale_shape_identity()</code></pre>
<hr />
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<hr />
<ul>
<li>We then desire to have shape 1 for our graph:</li>
</ul>
<pre class="r"><code>pc2 + geom_point(shape=1, size=4)</code></pre>
<hr />
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<hr />
<ul>
<li>This looks good but the original has thicker circles so we can play with this a little more to get</li>
</ul>
<pre class="r"><code>(pc3 &lt;- pc2 +
   geom_point(size = 4.2, shape = 1) +
   geom_point(size = 4.3, shape = 1) +
    geom_point(size = 4.1, shape = 1) +
   geom_point(size = 4, shape = 1) +
   geom_point(size = 3.9, shape = 1) +
   geom_point(size = 3.8, shape = 1)+
   geom_point(size = 3.5, shape = 1))</code></pre>
<hr />
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<hr />
</div>
<div id="label-select-points" class="section level2">
<h2>Label Select Points</h2>
<ul>
<li>With these labels there is no specific mathematical way to see why they were labeled. -This means we have to find a way to specifically label the ones we care about.</li>
<li>We then can use <code>geom_text()</code> to add labels to values.</li>
</ul>
<pre class="r"><code>pointsToLabel &lt;- c(&quot;Russia&quot;, &quot;Venezuela&quot;, &quot;Iraq&quot;, &quot;Myanmar&quot;, &quot;Sudan&quot;,
                   &quot;Afghanistan&quot;, &quot;Congo&quot;, &quot;Greece&quot;, &quot;Argentina&quot;, &quot;Brazil&quot;,
                   &quot;India&quot;, &quot;Italy&quot;, &quot;China&quot;, &quot;South Africa&quot;, &quot;Spane&quot;,
                   &quot;Botswana&quot;, &quot;Cape Verde&quot;, &quot;Bhutan&quot;, &quot;Rwanda&quot;, &quot;France&quot;,
                   &quot;United States&quot;, &quot;Germany&quot;, &quot;Britain&quot;, &quot;Barbados&quot;, &quot;Norway&quot;, &quot;Japan&quot;,
                   &quot;New Zealand&quot;, &quot;Singapore&quot;)</code></pre>
<hr />
</div>
<div id="label-select-points-1" class="section level2">
<h2>Label Select Points</h2>
<pre class="r"><code> pc3 +
  geom_text(aes(label = Country),
            color = &quot;gray20&quot;,
            data = subset(dat, Country %in% pointsToLabel))</code></pre>
<hr />
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<hr />
<ul>
<li>We notice that our text lays on top of the points here and it is hard to distinguish what point goes with which label.</li>
<li>We can solve this by using the <code>ggrepel</code> package:</li>
</ul>
<pre class="r"><code>library(&quot;ggrepel&quot;)
(pc4 &lt;-pc3 +
  geom_text_repel(aes(label = Country),
            color = &quot;gray20&quot;,
            data = subset(dat, Country %in% pointsToLabel),
            force = 10))</code></pre>
<hr />
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<hr />
</div>
<div id="change-region-labels-and-order." class="section level2">
<h2>Change Region Labels and Order.</h2>
<ul>
<li>We can do this by adjusting the factor <code>levels</code> and <code>labels</code>.</li>
</ul>
<pre class="r"><code>dat$Region &lt;- factor(dat$Region,
                     levels = c(&quot;EU W. Europe&quot;,
                                &quot;Americas&quot;,
                                &quot;Asia Pacific&quot;,
                                &quot;East EU Cemt Asia&quot;,
                                &quot;MENA&quot;,
                                &quot;SSA&quot;),
                     labels = c(&quot;OECD&quot;,
                                &quot;Americas&quot;,
                                &quot;Asia &amp;\nOceania&quot;,
                                &quot;Central &amp;\nEastern Europe&quot;,
                                &quot;Middle East &amp;\nNorth Africa&quot;,
                                &quot;Sub-Saharan\nAfrica&quot;))</code></pre>
<hr />
</div>
<div id="change-region-labels-and-order.-1" class="section level2">
<h2>Change Region Labels and Order.</h2>
<ul>
<li>We then need to tell the graph that we have called <code>pc4</code> above to use the new data that we have adjusted.</li>
</ul>
<pre class="r"><code>pc4$data &lt;- dat
 pc4</code></pre>
<hr />
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<hr />
</div>
<div id="add-title-and-format-axes." class="section level2">
<h2>Add title and format axes.</h2>
<ul>
<li>We can adjust the axes by using <code>scales</code> in ggplot2.</li>
<li>We can add a title to a plot using <code>ggtitle()</code>.</li>
</ul>
<pre class="r"><code>library(grid)
pc5 &lt;- pc4 +
  scale_x_continuous(name = &quot;Corruption Perceptions Index, 2011 (10=least corrupt)&quot;,
                     limits = c(.9, 10.5),
                     breaks = 1:10) +
  scale_y_continuous(name = &quot;Human Development Index, 2011 (1=Best)&quot;,
                     limits = c(0.2, 1.0),
                     breaks = seq(0.2, 1.0, by = 0.1)) +
  scale_color_manual(name = &quot;&quot;,
                     values = c(&quot;#24576D&quot;,
                                &quot;#099DD7&quot;,
                                &quot;#28AADC&quot;,
                                &quot;#248E84&quot;,
                                &quot;#F2583F&quot;,
                                &quot;#96503F&quot;)) +
  ggtitle(&quot;Corruption and Human development&quot;)</code></pre>
<hr />
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<hr />
</div>
<div id="final-changes-to-the-output." class="section level2">
<h2>Final Changes to the output.</h2>
<pre class="r"><code>pc6 &lt;- pc5 +
  theme_minimal() + # start with a minimal theme and add what we need
  theme(text = element_text(color = &quot;gray20&quot;),
        legend.position = c(&quot;top&quot;), # position the legend in the upper left 
        legend.direction = &quot;horizontal&quot;,
        legend.justification = 0.1, # anchor point for legend.position.
        legend.text = element_text(size = 11, color = &quot;gray10&quot;),
        axis.text = element_text(face = &quot;italic&quot;),
        axis.title.x = element_text(vjust=-10), # move title away from axis
        axis.title.y = element_text(vjust = 2), # move away for axis
        axis.ticks.y = element_blank(), # element_blank() is how we remove elements
        axis.line = element_line(color = &quot;gray40&quot;, size = 0.5),
        axis.line.y = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.major = element_line(color = &quot;gray50&quot;, size = 0.5),
        panel.grid.major.x = element_blank()
        )</code></pre>
<hr />
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<hr />
</div>
<div id="add-the-r2-to-the-plot." class="section level2">
<h2>Add the <span class="math inline">\(R^2\)</span> to the plot.</h2>
<pre class="r"><code>mR2 &lt;- summary(lm(HDI ~ log(CPI), data = dat))$r.squared</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code>library(grid)
#png(file = &quot;images/econScatter10.png&quot;, width = 800, height = 600)
pc6 
grid.text(&quot;Sources: Transparency International; UN Human Development Report&quot;,
         x = .01, y = .01,
         just = &quot;left&quot;,
         draw = TRUE,  gp=gpar(fontsize=7, col=&quot;grey&quot;))
grid.segments(x0 = 0.81, x1 = 0.825,
              y0 = 0.90, y1 = 0.90,
              gp = gpar(col = &quot;red&quot;),
              draw = TRUE)
grid.text(paste0(&quot;R? = &quot;,
                 as.integer(mR2*100),
                 &quot;%&quot;),
          x = 0.835, y = 0.90,
          gp = gpar(col = &quot;gray20&quot;),
          draw = TRUE,
          just = &quot;left&quot;)

#dev.off()</code></pre>
<hr />
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
</div>
</div>
